by the people of Amsterdam dur-
ing the Nazi occupation of their
country.

He told of how radios were
declared illegal during the Nazi
occupation. The penalty for pos-
session of one was death. On his
trip he heard stories of how peo-
ple would hide their radios in
ditches and bring them out at
night. Such acts of resistance
forced many into hiding.

Kahn said their resistance
should be a lesson to us.

“The most civil act is to be dis-
obedient,” Kahn said.

He suggests habits of resis-
tance as the only way to fight
against what he calls the fascist
attitudes in our own country;
These attitudes produce the
hatred directed against people of
color, women, homosexuals‘ and
bisexuals, Jews and the poor, all
who have had to learn these
habits of resistance for mere sur-
vival.

“We must refuse to cooperate
with injustice,” Kahn said.

He suggested we start by
developing an ability to recog-
nize evil and take action against
it, and also to refuse to make a
choice that will result in an injus-
tice.

We must stand together and for
one another, Kahn said. When a
man hears a. woman being sexu-
ally harassed, he should speak
against it. When white people
hear derogatory remarks about
African Americans, they should
not tolerate it.’

Such resistance is not easy,
Kahn said. It may require speak-
ing against a friend, family mem-
ber, co-worker or employer. It
may even be in defense of some-
one you do not like. But in order
to bridge the gaps in our society,
we must learn to practice these
habits of resistance each day
with completeness.

“This quiet power gives us
hope for the future,” Kahn said.
“In a world that is wracked by
hatred and violence, such habits

of resistance are all we have to

begin.”

