Pitt students, we are once again stunned by your apathy. This
Saturday there will be a concert held to beneﬁt Kevin Cecil, one of
our former peers. He was a student, that is, until someone shot him in
the back of the neck and made him a quadriplegic. He sat next to
some of you in classes, ate in the same cafeteria as you, maybe even
lived in the same apartment building as some of you. Yet very few of

you bought a ticket to attend the concert. V
' This benefit is not going to be a boring dinner filled with long I

speeches and lectures (sorry to ruin a possible excuse for not going);
it’s a concert Local bands, much like at the Rally Against Violence,
are performing at the beneﬁt to help Kevin Cecil. You would proba-
bly pay a cover charge to see them at a bar, so why not see the same
bands and give your money (tickets only cost $10) to a good cause?

Kevin Cecil is not a corporate charity serving faceless masses; that
excuse won’t work this time either. Kevin is a guy who was doing a
friend a favor by walking her home after dark, and now he needs
some friends to do him a favor. Even if you never heard of Kevin
Cecil before he was shot, you could easily have been in his place. If
you were, wouldn’t you want to know that the people you went to
school with were willing to help you?

Chemical arsenal mounts

According to the CIA, only the largest nuclear explosion could
destroy the chemical weapons plant that Libya is currently building
inside a mountain. Also according to the CIA, the facility will be the
“world’s largest ‘underground chemical weapons plant” (Pittsburgh
Tribune Review, March 25.) And ﬁnally, no one can stop the plant
from being built.’

The main question is this — why the hell notl? Libya, a known
enemy of the United States under the control of a known terrorist dic-
tator, is allowed to build a chemical weapons plant? The United
States is one of the few remaining superpowers, yet one of its ene-
mies is currently building the technology to destroy this country. And
there is no reason this should be allowed to happen.

The United States has met other countries in conﬂicts over lesser

causes. But now we seem to be willing to give Libya enough time to
create the weapons to kill every United States citizen. Chemical war-
fare is more tragic than any other combat, since the effects of many
weapons are unknown, long-lasting, and indiscriminate in who they
effect Entire populations of towns could be easily mowed down in a
few minutes, or over years.

The United States can not afford the risk of allowing Libya to cre-
ate a chemical arsenal. If nothing else was learned from past military
conﬂicts, we should at least recognize the potential for American sol-
diers to be tortured even after the war is over and they return home.

