Spring Break in Florida? I hope
you enjoyed them, because the
money you spent on these “luxu-
ries” could have been spent feed-
ing someone more needy than
you. If you’re not living at the
same level of the ‘most destitute
person, you are hypocritical to
complain.

Are these extreme examples?
Maybe, but where do you draw
the line? At what point do you
say that what you want is too

extravagant? Where we tend to .

do so is at other people’s posses-
sions. But most of you want to
succeed, so how will you like it
when someone tells you that

you ’re rich enough?

“But that’s what taxes are for!”
you cry. OK, then answer me
this: Suppose that I gave you
back all of the money that you
paid in taxes, ever. Would you
run out and give it back to all of
the organizations and individuals
that would have otherwise had it?

Let’s take it a step further.
Suppose you did decide, after I
gave youyour tax dollars back,
that you were going to be philan-
thropic about it. Would‘ you give
to all of the same people who
would have gotten your money?
Would you continue to subsidize
struggling small businesses, like
Amtrak?

Even if you stayed away from
corporate welfare, then we have
to bring up the cheats again. That
roommate of yours who collects

disability despite that fact there is

nothing wrong with him outside
of a shredded set‘ of morals. In the
current system he’s got your
money. Now you’ve got it back,
and he wants some. How much
will he get from you?

You may think that this is just a
question of screening, that even
though it will never be perfect,
certainly there are some people
who are undeniably deserving‘.
Like that 15 year-old girl that I
mentioned. Of course, what I
didn’t mention above is that
I didn’t inventher. She’s a real
person who borrowed other peo-
ple’s children, and faked crying in
public so that she could get
money for cigarettes and vodka.
She said it was a great way to get
sympathy.

Let’s even take away the cheats
and assume that this person
would normally have been a valid
recipient of assistance. But he is
also a totally reprehensible
human being. Just think about the
person you despise most, and
imagine him destitute. Don’t you
feel sorry for him that he’s unem-
ployed? Don’t you want to make
sure he has a comfortable life?
And there lies proof of the effi-
ciency of decentralization: no
agency could possibly make these
value judgments with your dollar
better than you, even and espe-
cially if you are attempting to
spend unselﬁshly.

There are people that I want to
help as much as possible. There

are groups that I believe in that I i

would like to give to. There are
also people, places and things that
I want nothing to do with. This
goes the same for you. And right
now, there are dollars of yours
going to people, groups and com-
panies that you don’t want to
help, while deserving people that
you may want to help have to
wait.

So I pose the question: which is
more cruel? -

